Entries.noAssertion: Makes no assertion about the field.

Entries.serious: The highest level of risk posed by an AI software.
Entries.high: The second-highest level of risk posed by an AI software.
Entries.medium: The third-highest level of risk posed by an AI software.
Entries.low: Low/no risk is posed by the AI software.

Entries.other: Used to store extra information about an Element which is not part of a Review (e.g. extra information provided during the creation of the Element).
Entries.review: Used when someone reviews the Element.

Entries.cve: An identifier for a specific software flaw defined within the official CVE Dictionary and that conforms to the CVE specification as defined by https://csrc.nist.gov/glossary/term/cve_id.
Entries.gitoid: https://www.iana.org/assignments/uri-schemes/prov/gitoid Gitoid stands for [Git Object ID](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Internals-Git-Objects) and a gitoid of type blob is a unique hash of a binary artifact. A gitoid may represent the software [Artifact ID](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/main/spec/SPEC.md#artifact-id) or the [OmniBOR Identifier](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/main/spec/SPEC.md#omnibor-identifier) for the software artifact's associated [OmniBOR Document](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/main/spec/SPEC.md#omnibor-document); this ambiguity exists because the OmniBOR Document is itself an artifact, and the gitoid of that artifact is its valid identifier. Omnibor is a minimalistic schema to describe software [Artifact Dependency Graphs](https://github.com/omnibor/spec/blob/main/spec/SPEC.md#artifact-dependency-graph-adg). Gitoids calculated on software artifacts (Snippet, File, or Package Elements) should be recorded in the SPDX 3.0 SoftwareArtifact's ContentIdentifier property. Gitoids calculated on the OmniBOR Document (OmniBOR Identifiers) should be recorded in the SPDX 3.0 Element's ExternalIdentifier property.
Entries.other: Used when the type doesn't match any of the other options.
Entries.securityOther: Used when there is a security related identifier of unspecified type.
Entries.urlScheme: the scheme used in order to locate a resource https://www.iana.org/assignments/uri-schemes/uri-schemes.xhtml

Entries.altDownloadLocation: A reference to an alternative download location.
Entries.altWebPage: A reference to an alternative web page.
Entries.binaryArtifact: A reference to binary artifacts related to a package.
Entries.buildMeta: A reference build metadata related to a published package.
Entries.buildSystem: A reference build system used to create or publish the package.
Entries.chat: A reference to the instant messaging system used by the maintainer for a package.
Entries.certificationReport: A reference to a certification report for a package from an accredited/independent body.
Entries.componentAnalysisReport: A reference to a Software Composition Analysis (SCA) report.
Entries.documentation: A reference to the documentation for a package.
Entries.dynamicAnalysisReport: A reference to a dynamic analysis report for a package.
Entries.eolNotice: A reference to the End Of Sale (EOS) and/or End Of Life (EOL) information related to a package.
Entries.exportControlAssessment: A reference to a export control assessment for a package.
Entries.funding: A reference to funding information related to a package.
Entries.issueTracker: A reference to the issue tracker for a package.
Entries.mailingList: A reference to the mailing list used by the maintainer for a package.
Entries.metrics: A reference to metrics related to package such as OpenSSF scorecards.
Entries.license: A reference to additional license information related to an artifact.
Entries.other: Used when the type doesn't match any of the other options.
Entries.privacyAssessment: A reference to a privacy assessment for a package.
Entries.productMetadata: A reference to additional product metadata such as reference within organization's product catalog.
Entries.purchaseOrder: A reference to a purchase order for a package.
Entries.releaseNotes: A reference to the release notes for a package.
Entries.releaseHistory: A reference to a published list of releases for a package.
Entries.riskAssessment: A reference to a risk assessment for a package.
Entries.runtimeAnalysisReport: A reference to a runtime analysis report for a package.
Entries.secureSoftwareAttestation: A reference to information assuring that the software is developed using security practices as defined by [NIST SP 800-218 Secure Software Development Framework (SSDF)](https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-218/final) or [CISA Secure Software Development Attestation Form](https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/2023-04/secure-software-self-attestation_common-form_508.pdf).
Entries.securityAdvisory: A reference to a published security advisory (where advisory as defined per ISO 29147:2018) that may affect one or more elements, e.g., vendor advisories or specific NVD entries.
Entries.securityAdversaryModel: A reference to the security adversary model for a package.
Entries.securityFix: A reference to the patch or source code that fixes a vulnerability.
Entries.securityOther: A reference to related security information of unspecified type.
Entries.securityPenTestReport: A reference to a [penetration test](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penetration_test) report for a package.
Entries.securityPolicy: A reference to instructions for reporting newly discovered security vulnerabilities for a package.
Entries.securityThreatModel: A reference the [security threat model](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Threat_model) for a package.
Entries.socialMedia: A reference to a social media channel for a package.
Entries.sourceArtifact: A reference to an artifact containing the sources for a package.
Entries.staticAnalysisReport: A reference to a static analysis report for a package.
Entries.support: A reference to the software support channel or other support information for a package.
Entries.vcs: A reference to a version control system related to a software artifact.
Entries.vulnerabilityDisclosureReport: A reference to a Vulnerability Disclosure Report (VDR) which provides the software supplier's analysis and findings describing the impact (or lack of impact) that reported vulnerabilities have on packages or products in the supplier's SBOM as defined in [NIST SP 800-161](https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-161/rev-1/final).
Entries.vulnerabilityExploitabilityAssessment: A reference to a Vulnerability Exploitability eXchange (VEX) statement which provides information on whether a product is impacted by a specific vulnerability in an included package and, if affected, whether there are actions recommended to remediate. See also [NTIA VEX one-page](https://ntia.gov/files/ntia/publications/vex_one-page_summary.pdf)..
Entries.qualityAssessmentReport: A reference to a quality assessment for a package.

Entries.blake2b256: blake2b algorithm with a digest size of 256 https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7693#section-4
Entries.blake2b384: blake2b algorithm with a digest size of 384 https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7693#section-4
Entries.blake2b512: blake2b algorithm with a digest size of 512 https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7693#section-4
Entries.other: any hashing algorithm that does not exist in this list of entries
Entries.sha224: secure hashing algorithm with a digest length of 224 https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/draft-ietf-pkix-sha224-01
Entries.sha256: secure hashing algorithm with a digest length of 256 https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4634
Entries.sha3_224: sha3 with a digest length of 224 https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/FIPS/NIST.FIPS.202.pdf
Entries.sha3_256: sha3 with a digest length of 256 https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/FIPS/NIST.FIPS.202.pdf
Entries.sha3_384: sha3 with a digest length of 384 https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/FIPS/NIST.FIPS.202.pdf
Entries.sha3_512: sha3 with a digest length of 512 https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/FIPS/NIST.FIPS.202.pdf
Entries.sha384: secure hashing algorithm with a digest length of 384 https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4634
Entries.sha512: secure hashing algorithm with a digest length of 512 https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4634

Entries.core: the element follows the Core profile specification
Entries.software: the element follows the Software profile specification
Entries.simpleLicensing: the element follows the simple Licensing profile specification
Entries.expandedLicensing: the element follows the expanded Licensing profile specification
Entries.security: the element follows the Security profile specification
Entries.build: the element follows the Build profile specification
Entries.ai: the element follows the AI profile specification
Entries.dataset: the element follows the Dataset profile specification
Entries.usage: the element follows the Usage profile specification
Entries.extension: the element follows the Extension profile specification

Entries.incomplete: The relationship is known not to be exhaustive.
Entries.complete: The relationship is known to be exhaustive.
Entries.noAssertion: There can be made no assertion about the completeness of the relationship.

Entries.affects: (Security/VEX) Designates one or more elements as affected by a vulnerability
Entries.ancestor: Every `to` Element is an ancestor of the `from` Element
Entries.availableFrom: This relationship is used to identify additional suppliers where an artifact is available from.
Entries.buildDependency: Every `to` Element is a build dependency of the `from` Element
Entries.buildTool: Build tool used to build an Element. This may be used to describe the build tool of a Build instance
Entries.coordinatedBy: (Security) Used to identify the vendor, researcher, or consumer agent performing coordination for a vulnerability
Entries.contains: Every `to` Element is contained by the `from` Element
Entries.configOf: (Build) Configuration information applied to an Element instance during a LifeycleScopeType period.  Example: Build configuration of the build instance
Entries.copy: Every `to` Element is a copy of the `from` Element
Entries.dataFile: Every `to` Element is a data file related to the the `from` Element
Entries.dependencyManifest: Every `to` Element is manifest file containing dependency information related to the `from` Element
Entries.dependsOn: Every `to` Element is a dependecy of the `from` Element
Entries.descendant: This relationship may be used to describe child builds of a Build instance.
Entries.describes: Every `to` Element is  described by the `from` Element.  This can be used to denote the root(s) of a tree of elements contained in an SBOM.
Entries.devDependency: Every `to` Element is a development dependency for the `from` Element
Entries.devTool: Every `to` Element is a development tool for the `from` Element
Entries.distributionArtifact: Every `to` Element is an artifact intended for distribution of the `from` Element (e.g. an RPM or archive file)
Entries.documentation: Every `to` Element is documentation for the `from` Element
Entries.doesNotAffect: (Security/VEX) Specifies a vulnerability has no impact on one or more elements
Entries.dynamicLink: Every `to` Element is dynamically linked to the `from` Element
Entries.example: Every `to` Element is an example for the `from` Element
Entries.evidenceFor: (Dataset) Every `to` Element is can be considered as evidence for the `from` Element
Entries.expandedFromArchive: Every `to` Element is an artifact expanded from the `from` archive file
Entries.exploitCreatedBy: (Security) Designates an agent has created an exploit against a vulnerability
Entries.fileAdded: Every `to` Element is is a file added to the `from` Element
Entries.fileDeleted: Every `to` Element is a file deleted from the `from` Element
Entries.fileModified: Every `to` Element is a modification of the `from` Element
Entries.fixedBy: (Security) Designates a vulnerability has been fixed by an agent
Entries.fixedIn: (Security/VEX) A vulnerability has been fixed in one or more elements
Entries.foundBy: (Security) Designates an agent was the original discoverer of a security vulnerability
Entries.generates: Every `to` Element is generated from the `from` Element
Entries.hasAssessmentFor: (Security) Relates a Vulnerability and an Element with a security assessment.
Entries.hasAssociatedVulnerability: (Security) Used to associate a security vulnerability with a software artifact
Entries.hostOf: (Build) The`from` Element in which every instance of the `to` Element during a LifecycleScopeType period runs on.   Example: host that the build runs on for an element.
Entries.inputOf: (Build) Input to the Element instance during a LifecycleScopeType period.   Example: input to the build instance for an element.
Entries.invokedBy: (Build) Every`to` Agent that invoked a `from` Element instance during a LifecycleScopeType period.  Example: Agent that invoked the build for an element
Entries.metafile: Every `to` Element is is a file containing metadata about the `from` Element
Entries.onBehalfOf: (Build) Every `to` Agent acting on behalf of another `from` Agent during a LifecycleScopeType period
Entries.optionalComponent: Every `to` Element is an optional component of the `from` Element
Entries.optionalDependency: Every `to` Element is an optional dependency of the `from` Element
Entries.other: Every `to` Element is related to the `from` Element where the relationship type is not described by any of the SPDX relationhip types
Entries.outputOf: (Build) `from` Element that is output `to` the Element instance during a LifecycleScopeType period.  Example: output of the build instance
Entries.packages: Every `to` Element is a packaged form of the `from` Element
Entries.patch: Every `to` Element is a patch for the `from` Element
Entries.prerequisite: Every `to` Element is a prerequisite of the `from` Element
Entries.providedDependency: Every `to` Element is a dependency not included in the distributed artifact but is assumed to be provided the `from` Element
Entries.publishedBy: (Security) Designates the agent that made a vulnerability record available for public use or reference
Entries.reportedBy: (Security) Designates the agent that first reported a vulnerability to the project, vendor, or tracking database for formal identification
Entries.republishedBy: (Security) Designates the agent that tracked, aggregated, and/or enriched vulnerability details to improve context (i.e. NVD)
Entries.requirementFor: Every `to` Element is required for the `from` Element
Entries.runtimeDependency: Every `to` Element is a runtime dependency for the `from` Element
Entries.specificationFor: Every `to` Element is a specification for the `from` Element
Entries.staticLink: Every `to` Element is statically linked to the `from` Element
Entries.test: Every `to` Element is a test artifact for the `from` Element
Entries.testCase: Every `to` Element is a test case for the `from` Element
Entries.testDependency: Every `to` Element is a test dependency for the `from` Element
Entries.testTool: Every `to` Element is a test tool for the `from` Element
Entries.testedOn: (AI, Dataset) The `from` Element has been tested on the `to` Element
Entries.trainedOn: (AI, Dataset) The `from` Element has been trained by the `to` Element(s)
Entries.underInvestigationFor: (Security/VEX) The impact of a vulnerability is being investigated
Entries.variant: Every `to` Element is a variant the `from` Element

Entries.Red: Data points in the dataset are highly confidential and can only be shared with named recipients.
Entries.Amber: Data points in the dataset can be shared only with specific organizations and their clients on a need to know basis.
Entries.Green: Dataset can be shared within a community of peers and partners.
Entries.Clear: Dataset may be distributed freely, without restriction.

Entries.Direct-Download: the dataset is publicly available and can be downloaded directly.
Entries.Scraping-Script: the dataset provider is not making available the underlying data and the dataset must be reassembled, typically using the provided script for scraping the data.
Entries.Query: the dataset is publicly available, but not all at once, and can only be accessed through queries which return parts of the dataset.
Entries.Clickthrough: the dataset is not publicly available and can only be accessed after affirmatively accepting terms on a clickthrough webpage.
Entries.Registration: the dataset is not publicly available and an email registration is required before accessing the dataset, although without an affirmative acceptance of terms.

Entries.structured: data is stored in tabular format or retrieved from a relational database.
Entries.numeric: data consists only of numeric entries.
Entries.text: data consists of unstructured text, such as a book, wikipedia article (without images), or transcript.
Entries.categorical: data that is classified into a discrete number of categories, such as the eye color of a population of people.
Entries.graph: data is in the form of a graph where entries are somehow related to each other through edges, such a social network of friends.
Entries.timeseries: data is recorded in an ordered sequence of timestamped entries, such as the price of a stock over the course of a day.
Entries.timestamp: data is recorded with a timestamp for each entry, but not necessarily ordered or at specific intervals, such as when a taxi ride starts and ends.
Entries.sensor: data is recorded from a physical sensor, such as a thermometer reading or biometric device.
Entries.image: data is a collection of images such as pictures of animals.
Entries.syntactic: data describes the syntax or semantics of a language or text, such as a parse tree used for natural language processing.
Entries.audio: data is audio based, such as a collection of music from the 80s.
Entries.video: data is video based, such as a collection of movie clips featuring Tom Hanks.
Entries.other: data is of a type not included in this list.

Entries.act: The vulnerability requires attention from the organization's internal, supervisory-level and leadership-level individuals. Necessary actions include requesting assistance or information about the vulnerability, as well as publishing a notification either internally and/or externally. Typically, internal groups would meet to determine the overall response and then execute agreed upon actions. CISA recommends remediating Act vulnerabilities as soon as possible.
Entries.attend: The vulnerability requires attention from the organization's internal, supervisory-level individuals. Necessary actions include requesting assistance or information about the vulnerability, and may involve publishing a notification either internally and/or externally. CISA recommends remediating Attend vulnerabilities sooner than standard update timelines.
Entries.track: The vulnerability does not require action at this time. The organization would continue to track the vulnerability and reassess it if new information becomes available. CISA recommends remediating Track vulnerabilities within standard update timelines.
Entries.trackStar: (Track* in the SSVC spec) The vulnerability contains specific characteristics that may require closer monitoring for changes. CISA recommends remediating Track* vulnerabilities within standard update timelines.

Entries.componentNotPresent: The software is not affected because the vulnerable component is not in the product.
Entries.vulnerableCodeNotPresent: The product is not affected because the code underlying the vulnerability is not present in the product.
Entries.vulnerableCodeCannotBeControlledByAdvers: The vulnerable component is present, and the component contains the vulnerable code. However, vulnerable code is used in such a way that an attacker cannot mount any anticipated attack.
Entries.vulnerableCodeNotInExecutePath: The affected code is not reachable through the execution of the code, including non-anticipated states of the product.
Entries.inlineMitigationsAlreadyExist: Built-in inline controls or mitigations prevent an adversary from leveraging the vulnerability.

Entries.design: SBOM of intended, planned software project or product with included components (some of which may not yet exist) for a new software artifact.
Entries.source: SBOM created directly from the development environment, source files, and included dependencies used to build an product artifact.
Entries.build: SBOM generated as part of the process of building the software to create a releasable artifact (e.g., executable or package) from data such as source files, dependencies, built components, build process ephemeral data, and other SBOMs.
Entries.deployed: SBOM provides an inventory of software that is present on a system. This may be an assembly of other SBOMs that combines analysis of configuration options, and examination of execution behavior in a (potentially simulated) deployment environment.
Entries.runtime: SBOM generated through instrumenting the system running the software, to capture only components present in the system, as well as external call-outs or dynamically loaded components. In some contexts, this may also be referred to as an “Instrumented” or “Dynamic” SBOM.
Entries.analyzed: SBOM generated through analysis of artifacts (e.g., executables, packages, containers, and virtual machine images) after its build. Such analysis generally requires a variety of heuristics. In some contexts, this may also be referred to as a “3rd party” SBOM.

Entries.application: the Element is a software application
Entries.archive: the Element is an archived collection of one or more files (.tar, .zip, etc)
Entries.bom: Element is a bill of materials
Entries.container: the Element is a container image which can be used by a container runtime application
Entries.device: the Element refers to a chipset, processor, or electronic board
Entries.evidence: the Element is the evidence that a specification or requirement has been fulfilled
Entries.executable: Element is an Artifact that can be run on a computer
Entries.file: the Element is a single file which can be independently distributed (configuration file, statically linked binary, Kubernetes deployment, etc)
Entries.firmware: the Element provides low level control over a device's hardware
Entries.framework: the Element is a software framework
Entries.install: the Element is used to install software on disk
Entries.library: the Element is a software library
Entries.manifest: the Element is a software manifest
Entries.model: the Element is a machine learning or artificial intelligence model
Entries.module: the Element is a module of a piece of software
Entries.operatingSystem: the Element is an operating system
Entries.other: the Element doesn't fit into any of the other categories
Entries.patch: Element contains a set of changes to update, fix, or improve another Element
Entries.requirement: the Element provides a requirement needed as input for another Element
Entries.source: the Element is a single or a collection of source files
Entries.specification: the Element is a plan, guideline or strategy how to create, perform or analyse an application
Entries.test: The Element is a test used to verify functionality on an software element
